			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Interesting. 
<br />

<br />
Blade Strike, I can understand -- Its MR not FR.
<br />

<br />
As for the others, I do know that I have seen several situations where resists are "spotty" in that a given spell will tend to either land for "full" or be totally resisted, with seemingly no middle ground. As I came to learn some of the OoW mobs, I found myself initially deciding that they were highly FR (or MR), only to come back to that spell later as the more effective of the two. I've been more worrying about winning encounters than running tests while raiding. You may be right, but I don't know either one of us has enough evidence one way or the other.
<br />

<br />

<br />
As far as I know, all other classes obtain a unique benefit from their OoW Ancients, or a very significant boost in power over all their other spells. Presently, mages appear to gain neither.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Still thinking through what a "right" approach for within-class spell balancing is, but my ideas so far are something like:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">1) Leave Bolt of Jerikor alone
<br />

<br />
2) Increase the mana efficiency and DPS of Star Strike so that for a Spec:Conj mage Star Strike is slightly higher mana efficiency but slightly lower DPS than for a Spec:Evoc mage using Bolt of Jerikor. </span>
<br />

<br />
This provides a "real choice" for all pre-Anguish OoW mages. Balance should hold over the range of gear/AAs up to, but not necessarily including Anguish (including modestly-equipped players).
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">3) Increase the mana efficiency and DPS of Ancient:Nova Strike so that for Anguish mages it is markedly superior to both Star Strike and Bolt of Jerikor. 
<br />
</span>
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
(I wish I could divorce this discussion from one of balancing, but it is difficult when this is one of the few meaningful upgrades past restoration of their PoP/GOD focus effects at level 70 a mage will see in Anguish. With the craptastic performance of our level 69, 70, and Ancient offensive spells, even restoring those focus effects is of little value. Even with "the best" OoW focus effects, you presently don't need to cast anything over level 68 to maximize performance.
<br />

<br />
I can't comment accurately on what Rogue and Melee DPS will be well into Anguish. Soulskive is already making it clear that Rogues are the DPS leaders in almost all situations. In my opinion, the DPS of A:NS, coupled with the long-overdue pet DPS upgrades, should place Anguish-level mages' raid DPS for encounters in the 5-10 minute range in amongst their Rogue peers' DPS. I am assuming that wizard DPS will have fallen off by that point.)<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.sovereignguild.org/forum/viewtopic.php?t=4429" target="_blank" class="postlink">Master Elementalist Itchyban of Veeshan</a>
<br />
"Nothing to see here. Move along. Move along." 
<br />
"These are not the droids you are looking for."</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
